362
00:27:18,566 --> 00:27:21,864
You need to wear good clothes
since you'll be in the spotlight.

363
00:27:22,949 --> 00:27:25,622
-But this is still--
-Don't think so hard about it.

364
00:27:26,624 --> 00:27:28,126
Just trust me.

365
00:27:34,138 --> 00:27:35,182
This way please.

366
00:28:06,704 --> 00:28:08,791
Fashion is just like men.

367
00:28:10,335 --> 00:28:13,008
Choose the one that fits you the best.

368
00:28:14,093 --> 00:28:15,345
Not the other way around.

369
00:28:17,934 --> 00:28:19,186
Even Ken?

370
00:28:19,896 --> 00:28:22,234
[chuckles] That's even simpler.

371
00:28:22,777 --> 00:28:25,324
I'm not dating his musical sense.

372
00:28:25,950 --> 00:28:27,996
I think he's a great songwriter.

373
00:28:29,290 --> 00:28:30,668
So they say.

374
00:28:34,885 --> 00:28:39,728
But he's better in bed than in the studio.

375
00:28:42,942 --> 00:28:47,535
[chuckles] Look, I'm already at this age.

376
00:28:48,621 --> 00:28:53,171
It will take some time
for you to get your freedom.

377
00:28:55,175 --> 00:28:58,473
[chuckles] Okay. This is yours too.

378
00:29:01,145 --> 00:29:02,607
You really look good in it.

379
00:29:16,885 --> 00:29:17,887
[door closes]

380
00:29:18,430 --> 00:29:19,432
[lock beeps]

381
00:29:39,013 --> 00:29:41,602
LIBERAL FRONTIER PARTY
HIROSHI MARUYAMA

382
00:29:51,663 --> 00:29:52,957
Do you have an appointment?

383
00:29:56,047 --> 00:29:58,594
[no audible dialogue]

384
00:30:01,432 --> 00:30:02,977
-[contact] We'll talk later.
-Okay.

385
00:30:09,031 --> 00:30:10,283
I'm Tamaki.

386
00:30:11,703 --> 00:30:14,083
We spoke on the phone.
I'm Kenichi Mashima.

387
00:30:14,166 --> 00:30:15,460
Nice to meet you.

388
00:30:16,672 --> 00:30:19,301
Is there a place
where we can speak privately?

389
00:30:20,888 --> 00:30:21,932
This way.

390
00:30:32,745 --> 00:30:36,377
What did our CEO do?

391
00:30:45,061 --> 00:30:46,314
Have a seat.

392
00:30:52,284 --> 00:30:54,121
He's in trouble, isn't he?

393
00:30:54,748 --> 00:30:57,962
Or someone like you wouldn't be here.

394
00:31:08,734 --> 00:31:12,115
He hasn't come to the office
in the past few days.

395
00:31:13,451 --> 00:31:18,461
Everyone here suspects
he's in some sort of trouble.

396
00:31:19,296 --> 00:31:25,266
I'm investigating Mr. Maruyama
and his case.

397
00:31:25,350 --> 00:31:26,352
I see.

398
00:31:26,853 --> 00:31:28,941
How's the company doing?

399
00:31:29,818 --> 00:31:31,070
Operationally?

400
00:31:32,322 --> 00:31:33,324
[sighs]

401
00:31:35,412 --> 00:31:40,631
Masashi's been spending money
like we're the most profitable in Japan.

402
00:31:41,215 --> 00:31:42,217
And in reality?

403
00:31:42,300 --> 00:31:44,179
[chuckles, inhales sharply]

404
00:31:45,265 --> 00:31:48,438
There was a time we couldn't pay
the employees.

405
00:31:49,023 --> 00:31:51,444
Which forced us to downsize the business.

406
00:31:51,528 --> 00:31:53,782
Then I was told we were doing well,

407
00:31:54,450 --> 00:31:57,874
but half the employees were
suddenly let go last week.

408
00:32:02,592 --> 00:32:04,178
And your government contracts?

409
00:32:04,846 --> 00:32:06,223
[stutters]

410
00:32:06,307 --> 00:32:07,309
Construction projects?

411
00:32:08,186 --> 00:32:09,396
Uh--

412
00:32:09,939 --> 00:32:15,283
Even indirectly, all our projects are
government projects.

413
00:32:15,366 --> 00:32:20,753
Was Hiroshi Maruyama involved
in those contracts?

414
00:32:20,836 --> 00:32:24,218
No, but he frequently visited our office.

415
00:32:25,345 --> 00:32:27,809
Were they involved in anything?

416
00:32:27,892 --> 00:32:30,396
Well-- [chuckles, inhales sharply]

417
00:32:30,480 --> 00:32:34,113
Neither of them are that stupid.

418
00:32:34,864 --> 00:32:40,208
But Masashi is always bragging about
having a brother who's a great politician.

419
00:32:40,876 --> 00:32:44,299
Saying he can get anything
if he asks his brother.

420
00:32:44,383 --> 00:32:45,385
"Get anything"?

421
00:32:45,886 --> 00:32:48,725
-Like what?
-Anything he asks for.

422
00:32:48,809 --> 00:32:52,399
He was telling everyone to call him
if they run into any problems,

423
00:32:52,482 --> 00:32:56,741
ordering Miyazaki beef at company parties,

424
00:32:56,825 --> 00:32:59,956
and giving expensive gifts
and trips overseas.

425
00:33:00,039 --> 00:33:04,089
But the company was deep in the red.

426
00:33:04,173 --> 00:33:05,634
It's a complete mess.

427
00:33:06,177 --> 00:33:07,179
I see.

428
00:33:15,445 --> 00:33:16,948
[door opens]

429
00:33:19,286 --> 00:33:20,288
[door closes]

430
00:33:24,379 --> 00:33:26,342
[footsteps approaching]

431
00:33:31,811 --> 00:33:33,022
[stranger] Mr. Maruyama?

432
00:33:34,274 --> 00:33:35,443
[Masashi] Yeah.

433
00:33:36,487 --> 00:33:37,907
Who are you?

434
00:33:39,243 --> 00:33:41,623
[stranger]
Were you expecting someone different?

435
00:33:42,833 --> 00:33:44,671
No, I wasn't really.

436
00:33:46,675 --> 00:33:47,927
[stranger] Don't worry.

437
00:33:48,845 --> 00:33:51,810
I know exactly why you're here.

438
00:33:52,937 --> 00:33:54,106
What do you mean?

439
00:33:55,526 --> 00:33:59,659
You want to do something about that woman
accusing you of assault, right?

440
00:34:04,251 --> 00:34:07,340
So, should I just shut her up?

441
00:34:09,512 --> 00:34:12,350
Or make her want nothing to do with you?
What will it be?

442
00:34:13,394 --> 00:34:15,607
I only want her to withdraw
her accusation.

443
00:34:17,027 --> 00:34:18,112
[stranger, in English] Okay.

444
00:34:19,114 --> 00:34:20,743
[in Japanese] That's easy to do.

445
00:34:20,826 --> 00:34:21,828
Hey.

446
00:34:29,844 --> 00:34:31,598
[in English] You must be kidding me.

447
00:34:34,394 --> 00:34:35,898
What do you mean
you can't print the story?

448
00:34:36,649 --> 00:34:38,987
-[sighs] Look. There's no story…
-[scoffs]

449
00:34:39,071 --> 00:34:40,699
-For fuck's sake.
-…okay. It's just speculation!

450
00:34:40,783 --> 00:34:42,369
You have no proof it wasn't a suicide!

451
00:34:42,452 --> 00:34:43,789
So it just disappears?

452
00:34:43,872 --> 00:34:44,874
[sighs]

453
00:34:44,957 --> 00:34:48,507
Who said disappeared? There was
nothing there in the first place.

454
00:34:48,590 --> 00:34:52,430
Okay. Story about the cover-up.

455
00:34:54,644 --> 00:34:56,230
I don't know. Was there a cover-up?

456
00:34:56,313 --> 00:34:58,610
In Watergate, the cover-up was bigger
than the actual crime.

457
00:34:58,693 --> 00:35:00,656
A story about the cover-ups in Japan.

458
00:35:01,323 --> 00:35:04,622
You're just speculating now.
There's no story. There's no cover-up.

459
00:35:06,543 --> 00:35:09,757
The informant told me the government is
eager not to have anything--

460
00:35:09,841 --> 00:35:12,137
And I mean anything,
rise up as a scandal right now.

461
00:35:12,220 --> 00:35:15,476
They have people keeping everyone quiet
on these kind of things.

462
00:35:16,938 --> 00:35:20,988
Well, if you have anything more than
an unconfirmed informant

463
00:35:21,071 --> 00:35:23,535
about the government cover-up,
yes, we can print that.

464
00:35:24,035 --> 00:35:25,622
But you don't have anything!

465
00:36:14,887 --> 00:36:16,348
[in Japanese] Where were you?

466
00:36:16,849 --> 00:36:18,060
Working.

467
00:36:18,728 --> 00:36:20,941
Dinner with the investors. I texted you.

468
00:36:21,651 --> 00:36:22,903
Guess you didn't see it.

469
00:36:22,987 --> 00:36:24,657
[inhales deeply]

470
00:36:30,084 --> 00:36:31,378
